By Blessing Bature-Akpakpan, In light of the prevailing rising cases of drug abuse and criminal behaviours by young people across the country, a group, Two-Faith Inter-religious Youth Organisation, has mapped out plans to embark on nationwide campaigns at state ministries of education to create awareness for general counselling and on-line training of final year students in secondary schools. in a visit to the headquarters of the Nigeria Security and Civil Defence Corps (NSCDC) yesterday in Abuja, the National President of Two-Faith Inter-Religious Youth Organisation, Mr Hillary Henry, announced that the program is aimed at safeguarding the future of Nigeria through nationwide online training, focusing on the moral teaching of Islam and Christianity; in order to fight against drug abuse and anti-social behaviours. “In an effort to actualise the nationwide press briefing and online training against drugs, substance abuse and issues of insecurity, Two-Faith Inter-religious Youth Organisation aims to collaborate with the FCT minister of state, Zenith Bank Plc and former First Lady of Akwa Ibom State, Her Excellency Mrs Unoma Ekaette Godswill Akpabio. “The project shall include the distribution of face-masks to state ministries of education; to support the efforts to curb the spread of Covid-19 in government secondary schools in Nigeria,” he said. Also speaking, the Chief Imam of NSCDC, Abdullahi Adamu Ali, who was in company of the National Chaplain of NSCDC, Pastor John Paul, said that inadequate awareness about drugs, substance abuse and antisocial behaviour by young people in Nigeria is a contributory factor to issues of insurgency, violence and fall in national economy. 